ionships. Charting the literary impact of William James, Charles Darwin, Friedrich Nietzsche, and, in particular, Henri Bergson, this book contends that vitalist understandings of psychology, affect, and perception led to new situational and relational definitions of selfhood. As Moses demonstrates, the modernists stirred by these vital life lessons give us a sense of what psychic life looks like at its most intricate, complex, and unpredictable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCharacters and characteristics in literature. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 0aVitalism in literature. 4aHenri Bergson. 4aaesthetics. 4aemotions theory. 4aethics. 4aliterary character. 4amodernist literature. 4amoral character. 4apsychoanalysis (critiques of). 4athe psyche. 4avitalism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804791236zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804791236423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804791236.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles